Rory McIlroy of Northern Ireland plays his shot from the bunker on the 16th hole during the final round of the RBC Canadian Open. AFP/Minas Panagiotakis/Getty Images TORONTO - Rory McIlroy registered his first PGA Tour victory in 2022, retaining the Canadian Open crown just a few days ahead of the US Open. McIlroy defended his title with a two-stroke after carding an eight-under-par 62, to win ahead of Tony Finau. Finau carded a six-under 64 that put him alone in second on 263, just one stroke in front of compatriot Justin Thomas. It's McIlroyâ€™s 21st PGA Tour win of his career, pulling clear of Greg Norman's Tour title haul of 20. The Northern Ireland star McIlroy played in the PGA Tour event while a number of his colleagues competed at the Saudi-funded LIV Golf Series. The PGA Tour has suspended its members who played in the tournament.